  <a  name="services"></a>
    <div class="content-section-a">

        <div class="container">
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-5 col-sm-6">
                    <hr class="section-heading-spacer">
                    <div class="clearfix"></div>
                    <h2 class="section-heading">What is a CORS Proxy?</h2>
                    <p class="lead">
                        A CORS proxy is a service that allows access to resources from resources and websites which do not support <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross-origin_resource_sharing">Cross-origin Resource Sharing (CORS)</a>. This allows developers working locally to use resources on the web and in the cloud without needing to add CORS to remote resources and allows access to legacy systems that do not yet support CORS.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-lg-5 col-lg-offset-2 col-sm-6">
                    <img class="img-responsive" src="img/bw-cors.png" alt="">
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
        <!-- /.container -->

    </div>
    <!-- /.content-section-a -->

    <div class="content-section-b">

        <div class="container">

            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-5 col-lg-offset-1 col-sm-push-6  col-sm-6">
                    <hr class="section-heading-spacer">
                    <div class="clearfix"></div>
                    <h2 class="section-heading">How Does It Work?</h2>
                    <p class="lead">
                        CORS Camel does the heavy lifting for you! When you make a request to the service it proxies the request to the resource and returns the response with the correct headers set for CORS compatability.
                    </p>
                    <h3>How do I use CORS Camel?</h3>
                    <p class="lead">
                        To use CORS Camel, append the resource you are looking for in the request to CORS Camel (or use the form above). For example, to proxy <code>http://google.com</code> make a request like this: 
                        <br />
                        <a href="http://codecamel.com/http://google.com/">
                            <code>http://codecamel.com/http://google.com/</code>
                        </a>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Make sure you include the 'http://' or 'https://' portion of the resource you want proxied.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-lg-5 col-sm-pull-6  col-sm-6">
                    <img class="img-responsive" src="img/camel_right.png" alt="">
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
        <!-- /.container -->

    </div>
    <!-- /.content-section-b -->

    <div class="content-section-a">

        <div class="container">

            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-5 col-sm-6">
                    <hr class="section-heading-spacer">
                    <div class="clearfix"></div>
                    <h2 class="section-heading">Limitations</h2>
                    <p class="lead">
                        Currently only HTTP GET requests are supported for CORS proxying. POST and other requests are being investigated. Additionally, the current maximum response time is 10s to help weed out abusers. For longer lasting requests consider forking the project and setting up a mirror.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-lg-5 col-lg-offset-2 col-sm-6">
                    <img class="img-responsive" src="img/camel_left.png" alt="">
                </div>
